3. Correlation Matrix Heatmap¶

In [17]:
#Create a subplot with matplotlib
f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

# Create a correlation heatmap in seaborn of disability prevalence data set
prev_corr = sns.heatmap(prev_sub.corr(), annot = True, ax = ax)
  • All of these numbers are going to be related. This data is just on the prevalence of disabilities. There is not useful information to gather from this.
In [18]:
#Create a subplot with matplotlib
f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

# Create a correlation heatmap in seaborn of employment & poverty data set
employ_corr = sns.heatmap(employ_sub.corr(), annot = True, ax = ax)

Strong Positive Relationships: total_pop and employed_count, total_pop and poverty_count, employed_count and poverty_count, disability_poverty and poverty_gap, disability_poverty and no_disability_poverty

  • The higher the total population, the higher the number of people employed and the higher number of people in poverty.
  • The higher the number of disabled people in poverty, the higher gap there is between disabled and non-disabled people in poverty.
  • The higher the number of disabled people in poverty, the higher the number of people not disabled are in poverty as well.

Moderate Positive Relationships: disability_employed and no_disability_employed, employment_gap and poverty_gap

  • The higher the number of disabled people employed, the higher the number of non-disabled people employed are.
  • The higher gap there is between disabled and non-disabled people in poverty, the higher gap there is between disabled and non-disabled people in employment.

Strong Negative Relationships: employment_gap and disability_employed, no_disability_employed and no_disability_poverty

  • The higher the number of disabled people unemployed, the higher the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people.
  • The higher the number of non-disabled people are employed, the lower the number of non-disabled people are in poverty.

Moderate Negative Relationships: disability_employed and disability_poverty, no_disability_employed and disability_poverty

  • The higher the number of disabled people unemployed, the higher the number of disabled people in poverty.
  • The higher the number of disabled people in poverty, the lower the number of non-disabled people employed.
It sticks out that the gap between disabled and non-disabled people in both employment and poverty has a strong correlation with the number of disabled people employed and in poverty but little to no relationship with the number of non-disabled people employed and in poverty.¶
In [19]:
#Create a subplot with matplotlib
f,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))

# Create a correlation heatmap in seaborn of earn2 data set
earn_corr = sns.heatmap(earn_sub.corr(), annot = True, ax = ax)

Strong Positive Relationships: total_earnings and no_disability_earnings, total_earnings and disability_earnings, total_earnings and earnings_gap, total_earnings and min_wage_rate, no_disability_earnings and disability_earnings, no_disability_earnings and earnings_gap, no_disability_earnings and min_wage_rate, disability_earnings and min_wage_rate

  • The higher the total_earnings, the higher the earnings for disabled people, non-disabled people, the gap in amount earned between disabled and non-disabled people, and minimum wage.
  • The higher the gap in amount earned between disabled and non-disabled people, the higher the earnings of non-disabled people.
  • The higher the minimum wage, the higher the earnings of disabled and non-disabled people.

Moderate Positive Relationships: min_wage_rate and earnings_gap

  • The higher the minimum wage, the higher the gap in amount earned between disabled and non-disabled people.
It sticks out that there is a correlation between no_disability_earnings and earnings gap but not disability_earnings and earning_gap.¶
It sticks out that there is a correlation between min_wage_rate and earnings_gap.¶

7. Project Questions¶

Questions from 6.1¶

Is there a connection between state minimum wage and poverty level of people with disabilities?

  • People with disabilities earn more in states with higher minimum wages.

How does the prevalence of people with disabilities impact the community?

  • The gap between disabled people and non-disabled people in employment and poverty is likely dependent on the number of disabled people employed and in poverty.
Additional Questions that Have Arised¶
  • Why is there a connection between the number of disabled people employed and in poverty to the gap in employment and poverty but not one with those who are not disabled?
  • How do disability categories, race, age, and gender impact the correlations made above?

8. Hypotheses¶

  • The higher the number of disabled people in poverty, the higher gap there is between disabled and non-disabled people in poverty.
  • The higher the number of disabled people unemployed, the higher the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people.
  • The higher the minimum wage, the higher the gap in amount earned between disabled and non-disabled people.

The poverty levels of those who are disabled is spread out with the exception of those that have a "hearing" disability that has much lower levels of poverty compared to the rest of the groups. On the other hand, the type of disability significantly impacts the likelihood of employment. Those who have "hearing" disabilities are most likely to be employed, followed by "vision", "cognitive", "ambulatory", "independent-living", and least likely to be employed being those with a "self-care" disability.

White disabled people are less likely to be in poverty and in most states 40-60% are employed. Black disabled people are more likely to be in poverty and in most states 30-50% are employed. Asian disabled people are less likely to be in poverty and in most states 40-60% are employed but there are more outliers for this group. Hispanic diabled people are not more or less likely to be in poverty and in most states 30-70% are employed. Disabled people who do not fall under the above categories (other) are slightly more likely to be in poverty compared to white and asian disabled people and in most states 30-50% are employed.
